@Node MAIN "Finder HELP: Wildcards"

@{b}The AmigaDOS's Pattern Matching Wildcards...@{ub}

@{pari -6}@{lindent 8}
@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}?@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Matches any single character.@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}FI?E@{ub} would match @{b}FILE@{ub}, @{b}FINE@{ub} and @{b}FIRE@{ub} but not @{b}FIE@{ub}.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}#@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Matches the following expression 0 or more times.@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}FRE#D@{ub} would match @{b}FRE@{ub}, @{b}FRED@{ub}, @{b}FREDD@{ub}, @{b}FREDDD@{ub}, etc.  @{b}#?@{ub} will match anything.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}(a|b|c)@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Matches any one of the items seperated by @{ui}@{b}|@{ub}.@{line}
For example, @{b}(D#?G|C#?T)@{ub} would match @{b}DOG@{ub}, @{b}CAT@{ub}, @{b}DIG@{ub}, @{b}COT@{ub}, etc.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}~@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}The tilde, the upper left key on most keyboards, negates the following expression.  It matches all strings that do not match the expression.@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}F~(ROG)#?@{ub} will match @{b}FROM@{ub} but not @{b}FROG@{ub}.  @{b}~(J#?)@{ub} will match anything not starting with the letter @{b}J@{ub}.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}[abc]@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}A character class: matches only the characters in the class.@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}a[bcd]@{ub} will match @{b}ab@{ub}, @{b}ac@{ub} and @{b}ad@{ub} but not @{b}ae@{ub}.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}[~abc]@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}The tilde here indicates a negated character class: matches only the characters not in the class.@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}a[~bc]@{ub} will match @{b}ad@{ub} and @{b}ae@{ub} but not @{b}ab@{ub} and @{b}ac@{ub}.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}[a-z]@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Character range (only within character classes).@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}[a-z]@{ub} represents all the lowercase letters from @{b}a@{ub} to @{b}z@{ub}. @{b}[a-cx-z]#?@{ub} would match any name starting with the letters @{b}a@{ub}, @{b}b@{ub}, @{b}c@{ub}, @{b}x@{ub}, @{b}y@{ub} or @{b}z@{ub}.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}%@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}Matches the null string.@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}CA(M|%)P@{ub} will match @{b}CAMP@{ub} and @{b}CAP@{ub}.

@{par}@{fg highlight}@{b}'@{ub}@{fg text}@{line}
@{i}The apostrophe, found on most keyboards just to the left of the return key.  This character is used to declare the following character to be a literal character,
instead of a possible wildcard symbol.  This permits you to use the characters @{ui}@{b}#@{ub}, @{b}?@{ub}, @{b}|@{ub},
@{b}%@{ub}, @{b}(@{ub}, @{b})@{ub}, @{b}[@{ub}, @{b}]@{ub}, @{b}*@{ub}, @{b}~@{ub}@{i} and even an apostrophe as themselves.@{ui}@{line}
For example, @{b}YEAR#?'%@{ub} will match @{b}YEAR1989%@{ub}, @{b}YEAR1990%@{ub} but not @{b}YEAR1989@{ub} or @{b}YEAR1990@{ub} as would normally be the case

@{pari -10}@{lindent 18}
@{par}@{b}NOTE@{ub}: The term "expression", above, means either a single character (ex: @{b}#?@{ub}), or an alternation (ex: @{b}#(ab|cd|ef)@{ub}), or a character class (ex: @{b}#[a-zA-Z]@{ub}).
@{pard}@{body}@{line}


@{b}Pattern Matching Examples:@{ub}@{line}
@{pari -6}@{lindent 8}
@{par}@{b}A?B@{ub}@{line}
Matches any three letter names beginning with @{b}A@{ub} and ending with @{b}B@{ub}, such as @{b}AcB@{ub}, @{b}AzB@{ub} and @{b}alb@{ub}.

@{par}@{b}A#BC@{ub}@{line}
Matches any name beginning with @{b}A@{ub}, ending with @{b}C@{ub} and having any number of @{b}B@{ub}s in between, such as @{b}AC@{ub}, @{b}ABC@{ub}, @{b}ABBC@{ub}, @{b}ABBBC@{ub} and so on.

@{par}@{b}A#(BC)@{ub}@{line}
Matches any name beginning with @{b}A@{ub} and followed by any number of @{b}BC@{ub} combinations, such as @{b}ABC@{ub}, @{b}ABCBC@{ub}, @{b}ABCBCBC@{ub} and so on.

@{par}@{b}A(B|C)D@{ub}@{line}
Matches @{b}ABD@{ub} or @{b}ACD@{ub}.

@{par}@{b}ABC#?@{ub}@{line}
Matches any name beginning with @{b}ABC@{ub}, regardless of what follows, such as @{b}ABCD@{ub}, @{b}ABCDEF.info@{ub} or @{b}ABCXYZ@{ub}.

@{par}@{b}#?XYZ@{ub}@{line}
Matches any names ending in @{b}XYZ@{ub}, reguardless of what precedes it, such as @{b}ABCXYZ@{ub} and @{b}ABCDEFXYZ@{ub}.

@{par}@{b}[A-D]#?@{ub}@{line}
Matches any name beginning with @{b}A@{ub}, @{b}B@{ub}, @{b}C@{ub} or @{b}D@{ub}.

@{par}@{b}~(XYZ)@{ub}@{line}
Matches anything but @{b}XYZ@{ub}.

@{par}@{b}~(#?XYZ)@{ub}@{line}
Matches anything not ending in @{b}XYZ@{ub}.

@{par}@{b}A(B|D|%)#C@{ub}@{line}
Matches @{b}ABC@{ub}, @{b}ADC@{ub}, @{b}AC@{ub} (@{b}%@{ub} means the null string), @{b}ABCC@{ub}, @{b}ADCC@{ub}, @{b}ACCC@{ub} and so on.


@endnode
